2 HOUSE BILL 284
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Public Safety
4 5–145.1.
5 (a) A licensed dealer may not conduct business and store firearms at a location
6 unless:
7 (1) the premises on which the licensed dealer operates is equipped with
8 security features, including:
9 (i) equipment capable of filming and recording video footage inside
10 and outside buildings where firearms are stored;
11 (ii) at least one of the following features designed to prevent
12 unauthorized entry installed on all exterior doors and windows of all buildings where
13 firearms are stored:
14 1. bars;
15 2. security screens;
16 3. commercial grade metal doors;
17 4. grates; or
18 5. other physical barriers approved by the Secretary;
19 (iii) a burglary alarm system that is continually monitored; and
20 (iv) if practicable, physical barriers designed to prevent the use of
21 motor vehicles to breach all buildings where firearms are stored; or
22 (2) outside business hours, the licensed dealer locks all firearms stored on
23 the premises in:
24 (i) a vault;
25 (ii) a safe; or
26 (iii) a room or building that meets the requirements under item (1) of
27 this subsection.
28 (B) (1) A LICENSED DEALER WHO KNOWS OR REASONABLY SHOULD
29 KNOW THAT A BURGLARY, ATTEMPTED BURGLARY, ROBBERY, THEFT, OR ANY OTHER

HOUSE BILL 284 3
1 EVENT MAY HAVE COMPROMISED THE SECURITY FEATURES REQUIRED UNDER
2 SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION SHALL NOTIFY THE SECRETARY WITHIN 24
3 HOURS AFTER THE DEALER FIRST DISCOVERS THAT THE SECURITY FEATURES MAY
4 HAVE BEEN COMPROMISED.
5 (B) (1) A LICENSED DEALER SHALL NOTIFY THE SECRETARY WITHIN 24
6 HOURS AFTER THE DEALER FIRST HAS KNOWLEDGE THAT:
7 (I) THERE HAS BEEN A BURGLARY, ATTEMPTED BURGLARY,
8 ROBBERY, OR THEFT INVOLVING A FIREARM OR AMMUNITION AT THE PREMISES ON
9 WHICH THE LICENSED DEALER OPERATES OR WHERE FIREARMS ARE STORED; OR
10 (II) A SECURITY FEATURE REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION
11 (A)(1) OF THIS SECTION HAS BEEN COMPROMISED, INCLUDING:
12 1. THE FAILURE OF EQUIPMENT TO FILM AND RECORD
13 VIDEO FOOTAGE UNDER SUBSECTION (A)(1)(I) OF THIS SECTION;
14 2. THE FAILURE OF A FEATURE TO PREVENT
15 UNAUTHORIZED ENTRY UNDER SUBSECTION (A)(1)(II) OF THIS SECTION;
16 3. THE FAILURE OF A BURGLARY ALARM SYSTEM TO
17 ALLOW FOR MONITORING UNDER SUBSECTION (A)(1)(III) OF THIS SECTION; OR
18 4. THE FAILURE OF A PHYSICAL BARRIER TO PREVENT
19 A BREACH, IF UTILIZED UNDER SUBSECTION (A)(1)(IV) OF THIS SECTION.
20 (2) THE NOTICE REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
21 SUBSECTION IS IN ADDITION TO ANY REPORT MADE TO THE LOCAL LAW
22 ENFORCEMENT AGENCY OR THE BUREAU OF ALCOHOL, TOBACCO, FIREARMS AND
23 EXPLOSIVES.
24 [(b)] (C) (1) This subsection does not apply if the equipment or alarm system
25 became temporarily inoperable at no fault of the licensed dealer.
26 (2) A person who violates this section is subject to a civil penalty IMPOSED
27 BY THE SECRETARY:
28 (I) FOR A FIRST VIOLATION, NOT EXCEEDING $250; AND
29 (II) FOR A SECOND OR SUBSEQUENT VIOLATION, not exceeding
30 $1,000 imposed by the Secretary.

4 HOUSE BILL 284
1 (3) In addition to the penalty imposed under paragraph (2) of this
2 subsection, a person who knowingly and willfully violates this section is subject to:
3 (i) for a second offense, suspension of the person’s dealer’s license;
4 and
5 (ii) for a third or subsequent offense, revocation of the person’s
6 dealer’s license.
7 [(c)] (D) The Secretary shall adopt rules and regulations to determine whether
8 a licensed dealer has met the requirements of subsection (a) of this section.
9 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
10 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
